            <div type="emblem" n="e19"><!-- Change the value of n to "e" followed by the number of the emblem. Use two digits for all numbers. -->
                <pb n="62"/><!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                
                
                <div type="title" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>
                        <lb/><orig>Embleme</orig> 19. Of the Secrets of Nature.
                        <lb/>If you kill one of the fower, they will all suddenly <choice><orig>dye</orig>.
                    </head>
                </div>
                
                
                <div type="epigram" xml:lang="en">
                    <head><orig>Epigramme</orig> 19.</head>
                    <lg>
                        <l>Behold <choice><orig>foure</orig> brethen here together stand,</l>
                        <l>One having earth, water the next in hand,</l>
                        <l>The third holds <choice><orig>aire</orig>, and fire the fourth alone:</l>
                        <l>If you would all destroy, kill <choice><orig>onely</orig> one,</l>
                        <l>And they will all forthwith <choice><orig>resigne</orig><reg>resign</reg></choice> to death,</l>
                        <l>Their lives depending <choice><orig>joyntly</orig> on one breath.</l>
                    </lg>
                </div>
                
                
                <pb n="63"/> <!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                <div type="discourse" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>Discourse 19.</head>
                    <ab><!--Our convention will be that if we have break = "no" then it means that the word is broken across the line with a dash--> 
                        <lb/>The <choice><orig>Poetts</orig> <choice><orig>doe</orig> <choice><orig>feigne</orig><reg>feign</reg></choice> Geryon King of <choice><orig>Spayne</orig><reg>Spain</reg></choice> to have been <choice><orig>tricorporeall</orig><reg>tricorporeal</reg></choice>,<pc>-</pc><milestone unit="section" n="e03-01" /> <!-- Change the value of n to "e" plus the number of the emblem (in two digits), followed by a hyphen and then a two-digit count of sentence -->
                        <lb/>who had oxen of a purple <choice><orig>colour</orig>, which a <choice><orig>dogge</orig> with two heads, and a Dragon
                        <lb/>with seven were <choice><orig>chargd</orig><reg>charged</reg></choice> with as warders: and the same Geryon is reported to be
                        <lb/>the <choice><orig>Sonne</orig> of Chrysaor sprung from the blood of Medusa, and that Dragon the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>Sonne</orig> of Typhon, and Echidna: which things <choice><orig>agreing</orig><reg>agreeing</reg></choice> with <choice><orig>noe</orig> <choice><orig>hystory</orig><reg>history</reg></choice>, or truth
                        <lb/>of the matter, as it sounds, and making a <choice><orig>noyse</orig><reg>noise</reg></choice> in all <choice><orig>Chymicall</orig> <choice><orig>Allegoryes</orig><reg>Allegories</reg></choice>,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>they are not without added hereto by us: But by the three <choice><orig>bodyes</orig> of Geryon <choice><orig>wee</orig>
                        <lb/><orig>meane</orig> three faces beheld in one father, according to the sense of Hermes, or as<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>others would have it, <choice><orig>foure</orig>, having regard to <choice><orig>soe</orig> many Elements: For of a Qua
                        <lb break="no"/>drangle ought a triangle to be made, as that made of a circle, <choice><orig>soe</orig> this to <choice><orig>re
                        <lb break="no"/>turne</orig> into a cicle: And the consanguinity and <choice><orig>naturall</orig> conjunction of the
                        <lb/><orig>bodyes</orig> of Geryon, or the Elements is <choice><orig>soe</orig> great, that one being overcome or<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>killd</orig>, the rest <choice><orig>allso</orig> <choice><orig>dye</orig> of themselves and putrefy, without the administration
                        <lb/>of any <choice><orig>manuall</orig> force: As to things with two <choice><orig>bodyes</orig> it is <choice><orig>knowne</orig>, that one being
                        <lb/>dead, the other <choice><orig>allso</orig> <choice><orig>wasts</orig><reg>wastes</reg></choice> and consumes: as in Italy <choice><orig>wee</orig> have seen a boy<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>foure</orig> years of age with two <choice><orig>bodyes</orig>, who absconded the head of his brother cleaving
                        <lb/>to him, within his <choice><orig>owne</orig> body, the other parts hung <choice><orig>downe</orig> to the <choice><orig>navill</orig><reg>navil</reg></choice>, where
                        <lb/>they were bound or <choice><orig>joynd</orig> together: But if <choice><orig>hee</orig>, that hung <choice><orig>downe</orig>, and being
                        <lb/>much <choice><orig>lesse</orig>, was <choice><orig>carryed</orig> by the other, Should be <choice><orig>touchd</orig><reg>touched</reg></choice> about the hands or<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>feet too hard, the bigger did hereby <choice><orig>feele</orig> <choice><orig>paine</orig>, yea <choice><orig>allso</orig> hunger, if the <choice><orig>lesse</orig>
                        <lb/>wanted food: And this is the combination and sympathy of nature, whereby
                        <lb/>the members and parts of one body, or <choice><orig>joynd</orig> with another are mutually<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>moved and affected together; whereof if one sound and unhurt, yet<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>the other <choice><orig>doe</orig> not thereby necessarily continue sound and unhurt, but if
                        <lb/><choice><orig>greivously</orig><reg>grievously</reg></choice> hurt, the rest <choice><orig>doe</orig> <choice><orig>allso</orig> sympathize, and perish by the same<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>malady: <choice><orig>Soe</orig> if a <choice><orig>neighbour</orig> gains much, <choice><orig>noe</orig> profit thereby <choice><orig>accrews</orig><reg>accrues</reg></choice> to his<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>neighbour</orig>, but if <choice><orig>hee</orig> Suffers <choice><orig>losse</orig> by fire, his <choice><orig>neighbour</orig> receives much<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>damage: for your <choice><orig>affaires</orig><reg>affairs</reg></choice> are in danger when your <choice><orig>neighbours</orig> house <choice><orig>hath</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>taken fire: It is not therefore a thing contradictory to truth, for the other
                        <lb/>three to <choice><orig>dye</orig>, by the destruction of one of these <choice><orig>foure</orig> brethren, <choice><orig>seing</orig><reg>seeing</reg></choice> that
                        <lb/>it may happen <choice><orig>divers</orig> <choice><orig>wayes</orig>, either by finding the same ends as <choice><orig>beginings</orig>
                        <lb/>of life being <choice><orig>borne</orig> at one birth both by father and mother, as <choice><orig>wee</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>have read has happened to some, perhaps by the inclination of the
                        <lb/><orig>starrs</orig>, or by being <choice><orig>joyned</orig> together not <choice><orig>onely</orig> in <choice><orig>soules</orig>, but <choice><orig>allso</orig> ligaments
                        <lb/>of the body, or by consternation of mind, by strong imagination in time
                        <lb/>of pestilence, or by the vow of a league: A <choice><orig>certaine</orig> heathenish people
                        <lb/><choice><orig>livd</orig><reg>lived</reg></choice> by the name of Pythagoreans in the <choice><orig>Indyes</orig><reg>Indies</reg></choice> under the govern
                        <lb break="no"/>ment of the great <choice><orig>Mogull</orig><reg>Mogul</reg></choice> (who now reigns there the nineth of the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Successors of Tamberlan) amongst <choice><orig>whome</orig> this ancient <choice><orig>custome</orig> is hither
                        <lb break="no"/>to observed, that if the husband <choice><orig>dye</orig>, his wife is <choice><orig>burnd</orig> with fire, or as<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>now, lives perpetually in the highest infamy, deserted by all, and <choice><orig>es
                        <lb break="no"/>teemd</orig><reg>esteemed</reg></choice> as a dead woman, which was therefore done, that the wives<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>might not kill themselves by <choice><orig>poyson</orig> for their husbands, <choice><orig>unlesse</orig> <choice><orig>allso</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        
                        
                        
                        <pb n="64"/><fw>Discourse 19.</fw><!-- Page number of the actual manuscript, followed by the header on the page. -->
                        <lb/>they were willing to <choice><orig>dye</orig>: <choice><orig>Soe</orig> in the <choice><orig>Philosophicall</orig> <choice><orig>worke</orig>, one of the bre
                        <lb break="no"/>thren being dead, the other <choice><orig>doe</orig> <choice><orig>allso</orig> perish by fire, not compulsively, but
                        <lb/>voluntarily, that they may not survive in sorrow and infamy: or if one be
                        <lb/>assaulted with a club, sword, or stone, <choice><orig>hee</orig> will commence <choice><orig>civill</orig><reg>civil</reg></choice> <choice><orig>warre</orig> with
                        <lb/>his brethren, as appears in the <choice><orig>Gyants</orig><reg>Giants</reg></choice> sprung from the teeth of a dragon<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>opposing Jason, and elswhere <choice><orig>allso</orig> Cadmus, and <choice><orig>soe</orig> they will all fall by<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>mutuall</orig> destruction: For touch or hurt him that <choice><orig>carryes</orig> <choice><orig>aire</orig>, and <choice><orig>hee</orig> will
                        <lb/>insurge against those two together which are nearest to him, namely him
                        <lb/>that <choice><orig>carryes</orig> water, and him that <choice><orig>carryes</orig> fire, and these will on both sides<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>oppose themselves <choice><orig>agaynst</orig><reg>against</reg></choice> him that <choice><orig>carryes</orig> earth, and him that first promo
                        <lb break="no"/>ted the <choice><orig>quarrell</orig><reg>quarrel</reg></choice>, till they have given and received <choice><orig>mutuall</orig> wounds, of<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>which they <choice><orig>dye</orig>: For it is thus decreed amongst the brethren, that the more<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>earnestly and vehemently they love one another, if once they begin to hate,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>they are not to be reconciled, but pursue one another to death, as the most<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>bitter choler is generated from the sweetest honey in a <choice><orig>stomacke</orig><reg>stomach</reg></choice> too <choice><orig>hott</orig>, or the
                        <lb/>Liver being corrupted. Kill therefore him that is alive, but <choice><orig>soe</orig>, as being dead
                        <lb/>to quicken him <choice><orig>againe</orig>, otherwise the death of him <choice><orig>killd</orig> <choice><orig>avayles</orig> you nothing;<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>for death will manifest him, that is to say, after resurrection, and death,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>darkenesse</orig>, and the sea will fly from him, as Hermes asserts, and the Dragon<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>which <choice><orig>observd</orig><reg>observed</reg></choice> the holes will <choice><orig>avoyd</orig> the <choice><orig>rayes</orig><reg>rays</reg></choice> of the <choice><orig>Sunne</orig>, and our dead<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>Sonne</orig> <choice><orig>liveth</orig><reg>lives</reg></choice>, and the King <choice><orig>cometh</orig><reg>comes</reg></choice> by fire: Bellinus in his Metaphor in the<note place="margin">Chapt 3...</note>
                        <lb/>Rosary <choice><orig>signifyes</orig><reg>signifies</reg></choice> the same thing, saying: And let this be done, when you<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>have <choice><orig>drawne</orig> <choice><orig>mee</orig> partly from my nature, and my wife partly from her<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>nature, you must then <choice><orig>allso</orig> kill the natures, and <choice><orig>wee</orig> are quickened by<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>a new and <choice><orig>spirituall</orig> resurrection, <choice><orig>soe</orig> that afterwards <choice><orig>wee</orig> cannot <choice><orig>dye</orig><pc>. .</pc>
                    </ab>   
                </div>
                
